## Evidence interpretation

This is stronger than the previous T5d blocker text: Pentagon did create an
internal target trigger for Maya from Theo's message, and the app eventually
claimed that trigger and ran Maya in the target conversation.

It still does not close full autonomy:

- message-to-claim latency was about 5m37s, outside the 90s watchdog window
  used in the T5d observation;
- message-to-ACK latency was about 6m10s, also outside that window;
- the public MCP catalog still does not expose an explicit target-agent
  trigger_turn/claimable-trigger primitive with routing readback;
- this proof depended on later table/log readback and does not by itself prove
  a stable bounded SLA for easy/medium/hard/extra-hard autonomous handoffs.

Reclassified blocker: not "no target execution exists", but "target execution
exists through the internal trigger queue and is not yet exposed/proven as a
bounded public activation primitive."
